I was hoping to get a response to a hypothetical situation.
I realize there may be another more appropriate group to post
to, so feel free to direct me. However, the hypothetical situation
regards compression, so I'd like these folk's response.
Here goes the hypothetical situation:

        Say you are hired by a software company in your town to
research data compression so that you can come up with new algorithms
for their existing compression software that will increase compression
performance. Say you are told that you will work with the software
engineer who wrote the existing software. And say that you signed
an agreement not to devulge any information to anyone outside the
company regarding the software.
        Then you start work for the company only to find out that
no one (including the owner) will discuss the contents of the software
with you because they say they know nothing about the programs
that the software engineer wrote. You then find the software engineer
is living in another state, not answering his phone messages, and
not returning e-mail messages that he promised to respond to.
        You begin to feel something strange is going on, but you just
decide to rip into the code to see what has already been done. In doing
so, you find this commercially sold software totally loaded with
others' code which has been downloaded from various sites. Some of the
code clearly labeled "not for commercial sale or use". Ross Williams
stuff, etc.
        Then you find that this company which advertises that its software
contains 10 compression algorithms has one algorithm, say the freeze/melt,
running the whole show as four algorithms are turned off (but the
application mimicks them working), one algorithm is a total copy (word for
word) of the algorithm before it, and one algorithm averages 0% compression.
        THEN say your boss puts pressure on you to download the new, updated,
versions of these algorithms "now" and "this week" since he believes
that EVERYONE does it to sell it commercially.
        I could go on with this hypothetical setting, but I've already
eaten up enough bandwidth.
         So tell me please, do you consider this o.k. business practices?
        Would you work at this place, or quit immediately when directed
        to download even more of others' code?
        Would you turn the company in to someone?
        Would you contact the owners of the code to let them deal with it,
        afterall, assume you're a struggling student and you don't have
        funds to do much else.
        Is this really done by everyone?
        Would you feel that if you didn't do anything you're a crumb,
        since you could hypothetically watch the company sell site
        licenses for the said software for $1500?
        any other comments are appreciated....thanks for taking the time...


