Now, the questions.

>        So tell me please, do you consider this o.k. business practices?

No, this is not OK.  It never was, it isn't now, and it never will be.


>  Would you work at this place, or quit immediately when directed to download
>  even more of others' code?

Yes, I would work there, but just long enough to ensure my resume is up to
date.  I would ensure I have absolutely _nothing_ on the company grounds
that I would mind loosing (that includes, sweaters, posters, stuff on your
hard disk, etc.).  Make sure you have _nothing_ at home that could
concievebly belong to the company, not even copies.  Be very careful to
ensure you don't have any form of software that belongs to them,
_ESPECIALLY_ not source code for the product in question.  Things are
gonna hit the fan, and you don't want to get splattered.  All told,
I'd say that you should need only about a week to fire off the old resume,
contact all your head-hunter buddies, and get the ball rolling.  Do the
right thing, but make sure you look out for #1, especially if you have a
family that counts on you for food and heat.  Don't delay.

Don't do the code downloads.  There are tons of ways to stall, chew up
time, delete files, break the FTP connection, mess up a packed file, try to
compile the latest demo of some stupid software you got off a BBS, track
down false leads, take a day off, get sick, get involved in a commitee, etc.
All you need is enough time to make sure you have your resume up to snuff
and out on the street and that you can't be nailed for 'stealing' company
secrets.


>       Would you turn the company in to someone?

Yes.  That's what the SPA, FBI, and various other acronyms are for.  Do
it.  Contact the SPA first.


>       Would you contact the owners of the code to let them deal with it,
>       afterall, assume you're a struggling student and you don't have
>       funds to do much else.

Depend on who the owner is, but I'd make sure they found out through the
SPA or via an e-mail message.  Students are quite resourceful at finding
other jobs.  Getting out of your current situation (hypothetically, of
course) will cut your stress level considerably.


>       Is this really done by everyone?

No, it's not.  That's why there is so much stuff out there to steal.  More
than a few folks _are_ creating new stuff that is worth having.  Only a few
folks are trying to ride on their coattails.



>       Would you feel that if you didn't do anything you're a crumb,
>       since you could hypothetically watch the company sell site
>       licenses for the said software for $1500?

Yes, I would feel like a crumb.  I would think hard about it for a couple
of days, and then I'd do the various things (and maybe a few others)
mentioned above.  I would _NOT_ do anything malicious to the company
computers, software, source code libraries, etc.  That's for others to
decide.  You don't have to like it, you don't have to do it, and you don't
have to stop them single-handedly.


